[1] Cholera - Niger
Date: Fri, 3 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Panafrican News Agency (PANA) Daily Newswire [edited]

Cholera outbreak kills 32 in Niger
----------------------------------
A cholera outbreak in 3 regions of Niger has killed 32 persons among
1573 reported cases, the National Health Information Office (SNIS)
affirmed here Fri, 3 Sep 2004, in a preliminary report.
The epidemic hit Tillabery, Maradi and Diffa in the western, central
and eastern regions, respectively. But SNIS said health authorities
have set up a number of treatment camps delivering free care to
patients, predominantly women and children.
The director of SNIS, Dr Kairo Kara Kiari, said cholera was first reported at
the Lake Chad basin, especially at the Doro fishing port [see report from
Chad below], killing 1 of 25 patients, and then in the commune of Maradi,
where it killed 4 of the 17 affected persons. Kiari said the epidemic hit
the region of the Niger river and the Urban Community of Niamey [the capital]
when rains began in early June 2004.
SNIS noted that the Niger government, Japan, Italy, Canada and a
number of international bodies, including the WHO and UNICEF, have
provided the health sector with enough drugs to fight the disease.
Since 1970, cholera epidemics have perennially hit Niger, especially in areas
along the Niger river, the source of drinking water for most of the
population.
--
