[4] Cholera - Guinea, Sierra Leone
Date: Tue, 7 Sep 2004.
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: All Africa.com & UN Integrated Regional Information Networks [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200409070266.html>

Guinea-Sierra Leone: Death Toll From Cholera Outbreak Rises
-----------------------------------------------------------
The death toll from a cholera outbreak in Guinea and neighboring
Sierra Leone rose to 86 at the end of August 2004, the Federation of Red
Cross and Red Crescent Societies reported.
The Geneva-based Federation said in a statement on Mon, 6 Sep 2004,
that 561 cholera cases and 55 deaths had been recorded in Sierra
Leone up to 30 Aug 2004, giving a death rate of nearly 10 percent.
It said the Red Cross was making plans to deal with up to 4000 cases
of the highly infectious disease in the West African country.
The Federation said Guinea had reported 333 cases of cholera and 31
deaths up to 31 Aug 2004, but the situation there seemed to be under
control.
The disease 1st appeared in Guinea following exceptionally heavy
rainfall during the second half of July 2004. It spread to Sierra
Leone shortly afterwards.
The cholera outbreak in Sierra Leone is the 1st to be recorded in the
country since 1999, but the Federation noted that no proper
contingency planning had been put in place by the government to deal
with such an emergency.
The Federation said the cholera outbreak in Guinea was concentrated
in the capital Conakry and the nearby towns of Coyah, Kindia and
Forecariah, all of which lie close to the frontier with Sierra Leone.
--
