[7] Salmonellosis - UK (Northern Ireland)
Date: Thu, 9 Sep 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Belfast Telegraph [edited]
<http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/story.jsp?story=559935>

Doctors probe 2nd food bug outbreak
-----------------------------------
Doctors are probing Ulster's 2nd salmonella outbreak in 3 months.
The Eastern Health Board said the latest involved 13 people -- half
of them from the greater Belfast area -- who picked up the food bug
over the last 8 days. 5 of the total needed hospital treatment as a
result.
In July 2004, up to 100 people were struck down by salmonella in the
Downpatrick area. A final report on that outbreak is currently being
put together by Board chiefs.
Commenting on the latest outbreak, a spokesman said: "The Board
normally sees an increased prevalence of salmonella during the summer
as many people return from overseas holidays. This period also
presents seasonal risks to food hygiene, and people should be mindful
of the need to carefully refrigerate perishable foodstuffs and to
ensure these are used promptly.
[Byline: Nigel Gould]
